Title : Cheshire Crown Glass Company
Text : The '''Cheshire Crown Glass Company''' was established in 1812 in [[Cheshire, Massachusetts]] to take advantage of the high-quality sand ([[Silicon dioxide|silica]]) in the area.<ref name=lockwood>{{cite book|last=Lockwood|first=John H|title=Western Massachusetts; a history, 1636-1925|date=1926|publisher=Lewis historical publishing company, inc.|location=New York and Chicago|page=549-550|url=https://archive.org/stream/westernmassachus02lock#page/548/mode/2up|author2=Ernest Newton Bagg |author3=Walter S. Carson |author4=Herbert E. Riley |author5=Edward Boltwood |author6=Will L. Clark |accessdate=1 May 2014}}</ref> The company was organized by Darius Brown, John Brown, John D. Leland, Ambrose Kasson, and John Hunt, and incorporated in an act approved by [[Governor of Massachusetts|Massachusetts Governor]] [[Marcus Morton]] on February 25, 1815.<ref>{{cite web|title=1814 Chap. 0148. An Act To Incorporate The Cheshire Crown Glass Company|url=http://archives.lib.state.ma.us/actsResolves/1814/1814acts0148.pdf|work=Acts and Resolves|publisher=State of Massachusetts|accessdate=1 May 2014|date=1814}}</ref> The capitalist behind the company, Captain Daniel Brown (father to Darius and John), ran a store and distillery in conjunction with the glass works.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Gazetteer of Berkshire County, Mass., 1725-1885|date=1885|page=30|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=W3YUAAAAYAAJ&lpg=PA30&ots=fLDwJzj53n&dq=Cheshire%20Crown%20Glass%20Company&pg=PA30#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=5 May 2014|editor1-first=Hamilton|editor1-last=Child|publisher=Printed at the Journal Office}}</ref>

The company produced [[Crown glass (window)|crown glass]] for windows, using sand from the "Lane bed" in nearby [[Lanesborough, Massachusetts]].<ref name=raynor>{{cite book|last=Raynor|first=Ellen M|title=History of the Town of Cheshire, Berkshire County, Mass|date=1885|publisher=C.W. Bryan & Company, Printers|page=97|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=S2u4ugVqxMMC&lpg=PA97&ots=g1YUAYK3Zf&dq=cheshire%20crown%20glass&pg=PA97#v=onepage&q&f=false|author2=Emma L. Petitclerc|accessdate=1 May 2014}}</ref> However, the company was not successful, and closed down only a few years later in 1816.<ref name=lockwood /> Unknown to the owners of the Cheshire Crown Glass Company, the factory was built over sand of even finer quality than that of the Lane bed.<ref name=raynor /> This bed of sand was discovered under the ruins of the factory in 1845, and led to the founding of the [[Berkshire Glass Company]].<ref name=patriquin>{{cite book|last=Patriquin|first=William J|title=The Berkshire Glass Works|date=2011|publisher=The History Press|page=14|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fXEUE2-hFJ0C&lpg=PA14&ots=CgnFNC5wfy&dq=cheshire%20crown%20glass&pg=PA14#v=onepage&q&f=false|author2=Julie L. Sloan|accessdate=1 May 2014}}</ref>

